<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-780-236  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 780 236.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Executive  Summer 1990 v3 n3 p28(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Formulating a systems integration plan.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bowman, Brent J.; Grupe, Fritz H.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>There are six types of systems integration: horizontal,application systems that cross functional business lines;vertical, applications that give information up and down themanagement hierarchy; physical, integration between locations;gateway, inter-organizational connection of information systems;and temporal, integration over time.andP;  The main issues informulating a systems integration plan are the technologyplatform, the enterprise data model, the applicationsarchitecture, and the implementation strategy.andP;  Planning questionsinclude: what goals are to be achieved; is the purpose clear anddesirable; does top management support the idea; is there a strongadvocate; who is the responsible manager; is the technologyplatform to be based on proprietary or industry-wide standards; isthe hardware platform compatible; is the software compatible; arethe expectations realistic; and can short term actions be derivedfrom the long range plan.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ManagementSystem DesignPlanningIntegrated Systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Types of system integration. (table)List of integration planning questions. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>